"absolute worst nightmare ever". I dream every night, sometimes multiple dreams but usually one really long one. It usually makes sense for the most part, is complex and follows a plot or story, like an art-house movie. I remember almost all of them at least for the day!

remember I've had this dream before and sort of know what I have to do to end it. I used to have 5/6 nightmares a week and thought it was normal, now I'm down to maybe 3 every two weeks and the severity has decreased - my normal nightmares used to be most people's--

I dream in extreme vividness, colour, smell, pain, pleasure, all sensations. I often lucid dream, can go back into dreams, have reoccurring dreams and nightmares - same dream and place, same place different dream - I even often have dreams years apart where in the dream I--

I wanna know how you dream! Do you dream in colour? 1st or 3rd person? Do you dream smells? Pain? Pleasure? Do you lucid dream? Do you remember them? Can you go back into a dream if you wake up from one? Reoccurring dreams? Do you have nightmares? How often? What's your 'normal'?

and slippers and grabbed my toy bunny and toddled down. My mum went to put me back to bed but a guest jovially asked me if I had any 'party tricks'.

I stood there and recited poetry because I was obsessed with it, and had memorised several pieces. They loved it.

I was never NT.

I need from them to actually be able to thrive, not just lie and wriggle my way through life.

I'll always laugh at this story, though. When I was very young, around 6, I came downstairs one night while my parents were having a dinner party. I put on my nicest dressing gown--

Even back then I knew I could crumble the whole thing.

Like I said, I'm a lot more okay with everything and myself, now. I have friends I don't HAVE to mask around. I let myself ask for explicit clarification. I explain to people I'm ND, why that matters in context, and what--

from her friends singing my praises! It was *ridiculous*. It is ridiculous! And honestly? It's scary. So much of what I have is because I know how to play the part of NT to a T. So many of those people wouldn't like me if they actually knew me, and that fucked me up as a kid.--

Spoilers: I could. Flawlessly. Pals, when I say I was the EPITOME of mid/upper class white british charming young woman, I am not exaggerating. And the WHOLE time all I could think was "holy shit, this is a language and a culture, and it is not *me*". My mum got LETTERS--

But last summer, when things were calmer pandemic wise, I had the opportunity to go to an outdoor / open air 'party' with a bunch of my parent's friends (masks, vaxx'd, neg tests etc).

And I decided to experiment. Could I, with all this knowledge, Play The Part? Again?--

If you need to, use a loose hair tie or ribbon to cinch them (but don't cut off blood flow!), and reinforce this with gloves and socks. Try to make sure your air isn't escaping out from your neck - you can tuck a scarf in between layers - and wear a hat or a head covering! 3/-

- Clean my dishes or the bathroom or help me tidy up a space I'm overwhelmed by

- Show me something YOU'RE doing! Don't require a response, but give me something to think positively about.

More hardcore stuff:
- Come cook me a meal. order me a pizza.
- Come hang out in my space without needing me to engage, make me cups of tea, just Be There

I've done it until after or sometimes in the middle. Much less of an unhindered reaction to a sensory or emotional stimulus (usually positive) and more 'my co-pilot tim in this jaeger is tripping on acid and i don't have full control of the robot' lol

but it's generally triggered by a positive emotion and is more along the lines of 'toddler brain is happy so we do toddler-level impulse things'.

A tic isn't an indulgence, it happens and I either have no idea or a very vague idea of what's going to happen, or I don't know -

how much control / knowledge of what I'm going to do / harmfulness of inappropriateness of the action as to whether it's just a tic or a tic+. A tic+ is generally more like indulging in an impulse I know isn't going to be offensive or harmful. It might be childish or 'silly' -

Tic + Stim: clapping when happy
Tic + ADHD: Touching / slapping / pinching things 
Stim + Tic: singing the same bit of song I love
ADHD + Tic: Touching / Patting / Suddenly hugging people when i get a surge of affection

I basically (incorrectly perhaps) mentally sort them by -

ADHD impulse: desperate longing to turn off the hot water switch outside the bathroom when my flatmate is showering every time it's on and i walk past it.
Stim: flapping hands when happy.
Tic: Winking, yelling, flipping the bird, "turn left", etc.

and then...

By that i mean like... sometimes a tic is a tic. Sometimes a tic is an adhd impulse. sometimes a tic is a stim. sometimes an adhd impulse is a tic. sometimes a stim is an adhd impulse. sometimes a stim is a stim. etc etc etc. i'm trying to get over my obsession with sorting them.

He nodded his head sagely, turned to the younger guy, and said:

"I'd like you to book them in for a second assessment, this one for ADHD."

And the guy was like "... *Oh*. Oh, yeah. "

So my bag got me my diagnosis!

@LaTiaJacquise fresh panties, pads, keys, loose change, loose keyrings, crushed packets of sweets, four different kinds of medicine, so many receipts, Just Trash, two wallets (neither in use), a book, pens, a notebook, a small toy I'd meant to give my brother years ago, a bag of cat treats, --

@LaTiaJacquise ABSOLUTELY EVERYTHING I COULD EVER NEED in a huge bag and hauling it around with me. He asked me if I'd be comfortable going through my bag with them, and internally I was like 'lol wtf is this about' but I was like "uh, sure?" and I started pulling out: pairs of socks, --

@LaTiaJacquise introduced himself and noticed I had a huge deep bag with a shoulder strap with me. He asked if it was my 'handbag' and I said yes, and he asked if I often forgot things or lost things, and I - very proudly - told him I USED to, but I combatted that by putting --

@LaTiaJacquise Okay! So I was being interviewed for bipolar because I'd been unwell and struggling for years and it runs heavily in my family, and the young doctor took the results of the test to the supervising psychiatrist, who called me into his office. He was really nice, --

pals, it's tough. it's so, so tough and i want to change but idk if i even can, and it's so much work keeping on top of even -

I had a pal round a few weeks back and did a really difficult fabric hoard clear out, and it went great! But now I'm left with the really hard stuff. The stuff I still like. The emotionally huge decisions. Annoyingly hard stuff to get rid off, Stuff IDK What To Do With At All. -

off my desk. The trash goes in a bin bag which sits in my room until full and then gets thrown out, the stuff gets moved around and around. 

I have a huge crate of stuff for the charity shop by the front door already. Earlier this year I already did all the easy stuff! -

moving and sorting and throwing away my things??? Absolutely not!!!

So I try to tidy. I take a pile of stuff. I put it somewhere else. Maybe I put two bags of stuff into one bag. Maybe I manage to cram some more into a cupboard. I clear the majority of the stuff (and trash) -

come in and just do it all for me, but I can't. I could afford to financially, but emotionally? The thought of someone 1) seeing the state I live in and 2) seeing the accumulated filth because there's too much stuff to get in with a hoover or a duster, and 3) touching and -

I remember sitting on the stairs in a flat in 2015, sobbing over throwing out a few doll boxes and a coat belonging to my aunt. I remember throwing things out belonging to her in 2010 and being inconsolable. It's HARD, y'all. And it's embarrassing. I'd love to pay someone to -

I know people know it's not as easy as 'tidy up' or 'get rid of things' for a hoarder, but holy fuck, when you have to do an internal song and dance about every. single. item? it's exhausting and upsetting and frustrating. I still remember sentimental items I threw out. -

My brain isn't good with memories anyway, you should hold on to it! Right, what about scraps of fabric? Well they're polyester, so if you throw them away they'll be dangerous for wildlife. Best to hold on to them and use them to stuff something, like a cushion or--... you see? -

Okay, what about this broken decorative thimble which belonged to your aunt and was in that printer's tray on her wall over 11 years ago (that she def didn't give a crap about), what about getting rid of that? Well, what if I forget the tray? The wall? My aunt, as a whole? -

Now throw in that my brain tells me every single item is either Useful or Important, sometimes both. Okay sure, but we have two cardboard boxes so we can get rid of one, right? Well hey, remember that time you needed a box and didn't have one? Remember all those times? -

Throw in scraps of silk or phone boxes or cables and suddenly, yeah, I'm kind of hoarding trash. Now add in a huge amount of items with emotional weight because Grief and Trauma, then add in a huge collection of everything I've ever been into, and you start to see the scale. -

in cleaning. I'm lucky I don't hoard animals or trash - though 'trash' is always subjective, because recycler! I won't throw out the 43 empty cardboard boxes because they could be used for something! Same with the pile of thread off-cuts which fell on the floor 3 months ago! -

My hoarding is a blend of learned behaviour (I come from a family of hoarders), sentimental (due to grief and trauma), collector, and recycler. I hoard objects, and trash is only in my space because of it either being hard to access and throw out, and general difficulties -

has not only the strongest social stigma attached to it, making it extremely difficult to deal with externally, it's the thing I get the most defensive, aggressive, anxious, and genuinely angry over the most, making it super difficult to deal with internally, too. -

Out of all the many things I deal and struggle with due to a mix of ADHD, trauma, and learned responses, my hoarding is the most difficult to deal with. And I mean deal with in all and every sense of the word. I think almost beyond all my other 'faults', my hoarding -
